<br>
Example:<br>
1. Guy robes bank<br>
2. Guy takes hostages<br>
3. Police shoot guy with Colt .45<br>
<br>
Result: 1 Guy dead, 15 bank workers alive.  Without the quick take down of Guy, he could have killed those hostages with his own Colt .45.<br>
<br>
<br>
Sometimes people are having trouble in real life, I've known a few of these people.  They use EQ as an escape to get away from real life abuse, neglect, peer presure, whatever.  They log in when they get home from a day at school getting picked on, etc to talk to their friends, to have a good time - sometimes the only reason (and this isn't a good thing IMO) these people have to trudge thru the day at work/school is the simple fact that they know they will have real friends to turn to when they get home.<br>
<br>
I think the &quot;Parker&quot; guy from the article was very wrong when he stated that:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
&quot;The social component is big because it gives players a false sense of relationships and identity,&quot; Parker said. &quot;They say they have friends, but they don't know their names.&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Everquest relationships are very real, even if the identity is false.  I could compare this to talking on the telephone - is a telephone friendship you have with an inmate in the federal prison &quot;false&quot;?  Of course not, you know that person is there on the other end and you talk to them every day.  How is it different from EverQuest?  Its not.<br>
<br>
Maybe he says EQ relationships are false because he doesn't think they last forever?  And in most cases, they dont last forever, but neither do real life relationships.  Think about it, over the course of your life you, or at least most people, keep close to their parents -and MAYBE 1 or 2 lifelong friends they've known since gradeschool.  Everybody else they simply meet along the way, get to know, spend 2-10 years of their life with then things start to shy away.<br>
<br>
It kinda brings a tear to my eye when I think back to all the people I use to know, all the friends I've had - and now have forgotten (but never REALLY).  Hell, I remember swinging on the swingset in school with, at that time, my best pal.  I wish we woulda kept in contact.<br>
<br>
But I digress, I'll stop swaying away from the topic.  The point is, you log on to EQ to talk to your friends, they talk back and you know they are real.  Who cares if its really the opposite sex on the other end?  Or who cares if they are really a 46 year old mother of 2 who in your era (assuming the subject of my ramblings is, a GenX kid) is considered &quot;old&quot; but who you in EQ think is the coolest person.<br>
<br>
I guess it all comes down to not knowing all the facts.  I challenge this &quot;Parker&quot; guy from the news article to play EQ himself for 2 1/2 to 3 years like I have, then tell me if all these friendships I have in EQ are &quot;false&quot;.<br>
<br>
<br>
I dunno, maybe nothing I'm saying makes sense.  Whatever.<br>
<br>
peace~monty<br>
